The Interface Phase
Horseshoe or rectangle?
In October 1943, two years after bombs destroyed the British Parliament=E2=
=80=99s Commons Chamber in the Blitz of 1941, the House of Lords debated ho=
w to rebuild. Some MPs and Lords wanted to take the opportunity to rearrang=
e the Chamber in a horseshoe style, like the US Senate and House of Represe=
ntatives.=C2=A0
Others argued [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUctuwyAQ_Jpwq8XDD3zg0Et=
_w1pgY6NgsPDSKH9fkqithNjVwGpmZxwQrrk8zJFPYs9roceBJuH9jEiEhdUTyxK8EaPUauhn5k=
3vhR40C-dyLYg7hGioVGRHtTE4oJDTa4JzObDNcN-j7me8atBqlvI6KRz9hEIKQPT6zQvVB0wOD=
X5jeeSELJqN6Dgv6vMiv9q53-_dASUG2DFRV28NA5srtRrDd0jrx4YlEKzYEFtD9A1r7QER3BOD=
4rZA6KgW_MPPpv0XcVt9fomx9SwYyaXgs1BCcdXzTnSTtDBwJb0VoLWb2gqDVdMwOovOy_nS832=
V3VntSeBuncs7KyZlsrk8tfT8tjX18fXQ7Fpa3WsK9FgwgY3o307SO5CXt8uKCUsLyi9ALQYlBq=
Wl1KOSb-ea1b3ggx5GzRqzz20q_ZP-AMYJpHE] that they should retain the =E2=80=
=9Cadversarial rectangular pattern=E2=80=9D from before the bombing. Britis=
h Prime Minister Winston Churchill led team rectangle. Churchill believed t=
hat the layout of the space itself was responsible for the British two-part=
y system. The confrontational design -- with the Conservative Party on one =
side and the Labour Party directly across from them -- kept debates =E2=80=
=9Clively and robust.=E2=80=9D The design left no space for equivocation. Y=
ou=E2=80=99re with us, or you=E2=80=99re directly against us.=C2=A0
In his October 28, 1943 speech on the matter, Churchill delivered an all-ti=
me classic line:=C2=A0
We shape our buildings; thereafter, they shape us.
Churchill and his rectangle side won the day. To this day, Members of Parli=
ament can only switch allegiances by physically crossing the floor in plain=
 view.=C2=A0
We shape our buildings; thereafter, they shape us. The spaces in which we l=
ive, work, and play shape how we live, work, and play. Churchill was referr=
ing to physical buildings, of course. The state of the art computer at the =
time was Colossus, which Alan Turing and team used to break Axis codes duri=
ng World War II. Its interface was a series of switches and dials. Only a f=
ew people in the world needed to, or knew how to, operate it.=C2=A0
=E2=80=8B=E2=80=8B
Increasingly, though, the spaces in which we spend time are digital ones.=
=C2=A0
Each new phase of the internet -- Web 1.0, Web 2.0, and Mobile -- relied on=
 new digital spaces to attract consumers. From text-based to graphical to i=
nteractive to mobile apps, new interfaces brought new adoption. Each phase =
was enabled by new infrastructure beneath the surface and pushed to popular=
ity by the apps built on top, but each also required new interfaces to achi=
eve broad adoption.=C2=A0
We shape our interfaces; thereafter, they shape us.
While web3 apps like NFTs, DAOs, and DeFi are gaining popularity, we=E2=80=
=99re still interacting with web3 through web2 interfaces. If history is a =
guide, we=E2=80=99re going to need new web3-native interfaces and spaces to=
 bring hundreds of millions of people into the ecosystem.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s early, but there are clues of what new interfaces might look l=
ike. New digital spaces are springing up around the internet and evolving e=
very day. Wallets like MetaMask, Phantom, and Rainbow are changing how we l=
og in, and what we bring with us when we do. Web3 worlds like Decentraland,=
 Somnium Space, The Sandbox, and Cyber are reimagining how we experience an=
d interact online. They=E2=80=99re early components of the Metaverse, sure,=
 but this isn=E2=80=99t necessarily a Metaverse piece. It=E2=80=99s a piece=
 about the evolution of the way that we interact with, and on, the internet.
We=E2=80=99ve spent most of 2021 over here at Not Boring HQ exploring web3,=
 and hopefully we all understand what=E2=80=99s happening a little bit bett=
er because of it, but it=E2=80=99s still hard to feel the potential impact =
of web3 in our bones while we=E2=80=99re still using web2 interfaces. For w=
eb3 to become a part of our daily life in the way that the internet or mobi=
le is will require new spaces and interfaces.=C2=A0
Today, we=E2=80=99ll explore how those new interfaces and spaces might brin=
g web3 mainstream:=C2=A0
